n Whitton in Roxburghshire since the mid 12th century, when Walter <i>de Riddel</i>, from Rydale (North Yorkshire), settled in Scotland after accompanying King David. Another unrelated family of this name have been established in Northumberland since at least the 14th century, with William <i>de Ridell</i> having been sheriff of the county in 1314."],"variants":[{"name":"Riddle","meanings":["English:","habitational name probably chiefly from Ryedale, a river valley in North Yorkshire. The placename derives from the river name <i>Rye</i> (of uncertain etymology) + Old Norse <i>dalr</i> ‘valley’. There are, however, other places called Rydale (in Westmorland for example) which could have given rise to hereditary surnames.","of Norman origin, from an Old French personal name <i>Ridel</i>, perhaps a pet form of ancient Germanic names such as <i>Ridbald</i> and <i>Ridhari(us)</i>."]},{"name":"Ridall","meanings":["Scottish and English (Yorkshire and Lincolnshire): variant of   Riddell  ."]},{"name":"Riddel","meanings":["Scottish and English: variant of   Riddell  ; see   Riddle  ."]},{"name":"Rydell","meanings":["Swedish: ornamental name composed of the placename element <i>ryd</i> ‘woodland clearing’ + the suffix <i>-ell</i>, a derivative of the Latin adjectival ending <i>-elius</i>.","English: variant of   Riddell  ; see   Riddle  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Jonet","type":"FIRST","meanings":["A Scottish form of Janet."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Jonet Riddell was born about 1240, in Ayrshire, Scotland, her father, Sir Riddell of Glengarnock, was 22 and her mother, Lady Riddell of Glengarnock, was 22. She had at least 1 son with Reginald Cunningham 1st of Glengarnock. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"about 1240–":"umbes 1240–Surnud","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","1265–1310":"1265–1310","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1220–Female":"1220–Surnud","1310":"1310","1265":"1265","1220":"1220","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","ab